The seabed hides a world little known so far, rich in natural resources.
It contains oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also living organisms that are currently unknown, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A wider bottom than the firm ground
The coastal states have now begun to vehemently aspire to the new underwater territories.
According to a United Nations convention, they actually use their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of what is called the continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, in accordance with the Convention, claim exclusively all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To simplify, the continental shelf is considered the part of the seabed and its basement, which constitutes a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone,” explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation, based on many expensive prospections and metrology.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the Commission has dealt with five requests, those from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful,” Mikulka adds.
Australia’s success, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater holdings, has recently seen a global outpouring.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which the commission awarded to it last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, which represents the country's area multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefits they will reap in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they see fit, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their requests.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no longer any state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, we are not mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," says exaggerating Director Mikulka, adding that "its zones are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract".
Czechs in the Pacific
Today, part of the seabed also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern Bloc within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
It obtained in 1991, under the Convention, as well as investors from a few other States, the status of the so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area proposed by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is enlivened there, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
