Mark Brown writes: Musical director at Guildford since 1962, Vermon "Tod" Handley (died September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
Already part of his musical project for the city, he founded the following year, the fantastic youth choir, Proteus.
The choir was supposed to include children under 21, but before Proteus could sing his last song in 1979, many of us who were over 20 years old refused to abandon the choir.
The name "Proteus" (which changed shape according to mythology) represented the will and ability of the choir to handle any type of music presented to it, whether madrigal or Messianic.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often impressive, always exciting, thanks to the inspiration of a single man, and his enthusiasm for music, which remained constant over the years.
Remember how Tod used to tell us to “let the music speak for itself.”
He would have said, "The composer knows what he wants."
Everything is there, in the music.
So sing!"
His baton technique was absolutely clear, precise, even if never dictatorial or appearing.
Whatever the musical standard, he raised it much higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If a driver was to be named a knight, it would be Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the decades from 1962 to 1982, when he was conducting the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the past 40 years, I’ve seen more than a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that none of them have ever disappointed me—and, sometimes, they’ve even inspired me.
Tod Handley held so rarely this combination of grandeur and personal modesty.
