Morgan Stanley opens up its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan’s first bank, which will disburse nine billion dollars to take 21% of its capital, a new one welcomed by a sharp drop in its stock price.
A week after unveiling an interim agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s common stock at a unit price of $25.25, a total of $3 billion.
The retained price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities that will provide a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, 28% above its current price.
The Morgan Stanley stock, however, lost 6.79% to $23.07 at around 5:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, the group’s CEO.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new status last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but pass it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest names to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been amended in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, “we thought that participation would be entirely composed of ordinary shares.
But given the current state of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares in one year if they trade more than 50% above the conversion price, at approximately $47, for a given period.
Morgan Stanley ensures that MUFG’s capital will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
However, a spokesperson for the group declined to provide details on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to display a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan said he had "clearly" eased his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been grueling for the group, which has seen its stock price halve as the cost of insurance against a default risk on its debt soared.
This cost declined on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of Wall Street’s major investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refounding the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like its counterparts and friends, it was the third that put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The “Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil governorate headquarters, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As a matter of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales as well as his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place quietly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the state's power over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country living essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that it will use this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad.
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the captors of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive for ten days in the desert were returned safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived around 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at al-Maza military base, docked at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, on helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, to undergo examinations.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 on a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one cache to the other by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, carried on board two helicopters, launched the assault on the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of shots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," the official, who requested anonymity, said.
He said that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit had been sent to Sudan in total, where they received the support of German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned Belgrade, where he is located, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result through the professionalism and efficiency of our men of the secret services, of the special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were on board, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement had immediately denied.
