Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries support, to the amount of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution in Hong Kong.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, by also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been intensifying for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions that will be taken in the case of Fortis Bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy almost half (up to 49%) of the bank’s capital in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, including, first of all, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch company ABN Amro.
In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company's shares fell 12 percent, to its lowest level in 14 years.
Since January, shares have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's leaders, is not realistic.
The management of the company accuses the uncertainty of the overseas, in connection with the adoption of the American rescue plan of 700 billion dollars, of being the cause of the fall of the shares of Fortis.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private purchasers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Earlier, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they were not going to lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s customer circle and no agencies were taken on assailant.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information about the prescription of drugs, in any case, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting his chicken coop to a fox,” Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make insurance premiums and insured capital depend on the client’s health condition, and if they think the risk is too great, they don’t even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after learning of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much less expensive procedure: from an identification number, he easily provides himself with data on the person's drug purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines for himself, what disease the person suffers and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol-lowering, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or against hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others do not.
Companies have grown in data research and analysis, and they need to ask the patient for permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their past failures.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests, linking them to data on drug use, so they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of usage is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope of action extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to widen the scope of authorities' control over data supply companies is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus, and ultimately, the chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, issues.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit where there will be a focus on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is an emerging great democratic power that should be given a broader right to speak in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue, yesterday, at this 9th summit held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, like the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would multiply trade by two, which means a rise of a billion dollars.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the exchange of goods has increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious target.
In this sense, they have harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights from a legal point of view, so that air traffic can also take off in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with, on the one hand, India, which is the EU's top trading partner, and, on the other hand, New Delhi, which is only in ninth place among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan has been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this issue has been raised.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains true to the energy and climate agenda, including that it would like to reduce its toxic emissions by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as with the fact that a global market should be passed at the climate conference scheduled for next year, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to review the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is today in the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth twenty billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the press agency, the agreement would last for 15 years.
