Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying in the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, there is no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dismissed the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is indeed the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared," he said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the area.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (NTSB) reported that hours after the wreck was found, a team of investigators sent to the site identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing Fosset's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history through a long series of records.
On the sixth attempt, he became in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had toured the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters in height, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the ad you're not waiting for.
An unusual 4x4 of an original and well-defined design, with marked lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
Here, in summary, Glk, the latest born of the "compact" off-road of the star's house, with which Mercedes-Benz has tried to give a wind of novelty in this sector.
It is precisely because of its out-of-standard, unexpected and unconventional content that will be the communication that will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, available in Mercedes-Benz showrooms, from October 17th.
Thus, the hype that will accompany the start of the new car will give rise to an unprecedented mode of communication, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by a car brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, which will dominate the heart of Milan’s shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication involves the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, one will have the impression that when looking at the image, the car comes out of the poster.
Then, through the use of the innovative technology Elimina8, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recompose into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertising, Mercedes is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of automotive communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to arouse the interest of future buyers? We will see.
